# shadcn/ui Usage in This Project

> **ABSOLUTE RULE**: This project uses **shadcn/ui exclusively** for ALL UI elements. No custom UI components, custom-styled primitives, or raw HTML elements styled from scratch are permitted anywhere in this project. There are **zero exceptions**.

## Strict Requirements

- **No custom UI**: Do NOT create custom buttons, inputs, dialogs, cards, forms, navigation, modals, badges, alerts, or any other UI element from scratch. If a shadcn/ui component exists for the purpose, use it — period.
- **No inline ad-hoc styling** to simulate components that shadcn/ui already provides.
- **No third-party UI libraries** other than shadcn/ui (e.g. no MUI, Chakra, Mantine, Ant Design, etc.).

## Clerk Authentication UI

- **Sign In / Sign Up buttons**: Always use the shadcn/ui `Button` component for any Clerk sign-in or sign-up trigger. Do NOT use Clerk's pre-built `<SignInButton>` or `<SignUpButton>` rendered as raw HTML or with a custom-styled wrapper.
- **Modal mode**: Clerk's sign-in and sign-up flows **must** use modal mode. Set `mode="modal"` on `<SignInButton>` and `<SignUpButton>` so the auth UI launches in an overlay instead of navigating to a separate page.

Example:

```tsx
import { SignInButton, SignUpButton } from "@clerk/nextjs";
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";

<SignInButton mode="modal">
  <Button>Sign In</Button>
</SignInButton>

<SignUpButton mode="modal">
  <Button>Sign Up</Button>
</SignUpButton>
```

## Initialization

- **If shadcn/ui is not yet initialized in this project**, initialize it with:

```bash
npx shadcn@latest init
```

Use this command at the workspace root.

## Adding Components

- **If a particular shadcn/ui component is not yet installed**, add it using:

```bash
npx shadcn@latest add <component-name>
```

- For example, to add the `button` component:

```bash
npx shadcn@latest add button
```

## General Guidance

- Use shadcn/ui components and their composition patterns (variants, slots, etc.) for everything UI-related.
- Extend appearance only via the component's own variant/class props or Tailwind utility classes applied to an existing shadcn/ui component — never by replacing the component with a hand-rolled alternative.
- Keep theming consistent with shadcn/ui defaults (`globals.css` CSS variables). Modify the theme there rather than overriding individual components.
